# Scout Troop Gear Management System - Project Context

## Maintainer constraints (persistent)

- **Frontend-only by default:** The primary maintainer for this project works in **`frontend/`** only (Vite + React). **Do not edit** `backend/**`, Supabase DDL/migrations, or server/hosting config **unless** they explicitly request that change. **Do not include backend diffs** in commits or pushes that are meant to be frontend-only. If something truly requires a backend or database change, explain what is needed and let the backend owner implement it.
- **Rationale:** Keeps shared API and deployment ownership clear and avoids accidental backend changes on push.

## Background
I am an assistant scout master (ASM) for a Scouts BSA troop. One of my roles is quartermaster mentor which means I am in charge of the troop gear. I have just started this position and want to implement changes. Top of mind, I want to implement a digital online tracking system for troop gear. The current system is using a paper process.

## Technology Decision
After much research and consideration of budget constraints, I have decided to build an inventory management and checkout system using a **modern web stack with Vite + React frontend and Express.js backend**. 

**Key Requirements:**
- System needs to allow us to take inventory (e.g. 3 times a year)
- Have a check out/check in process that works on a mobile device
- **Mobile-first design is critical** - scouts will primarily use phones
- Budget-conscious solution using existing resources
- Our troop has its own server where I can run Node.js applications

## Architecture Decision
**Frontend:** Vite + React (mobile-first design)
**Backend:** Express.js with Node.js
**Data Storage:** Supabase (PostgreSQL) — single source of truth for all reads and writes
**Hosting:** Render (Node.js hosting)
**Mobile Experience:** Progressive web app capabilities, touch-optimized UI

## Codebase map (for agents)

- **`frontend/`** — Vite + React + Tailwind. Entry: `src/main.jsx` → `src/App.jsx`. Routing uses **`HashRouter`** (URLs look like `/#/cart`, `/#/manage-inventory`).
- **`frontend/src/pages/`** — User flows: `Landing`, `Categories`, `Items`, `Cart`, `Checkout`, `Success`; `Checkin` / `CheckinForm`; `CheckoutOptions`, `Reservations`, `ReservationInfo`, `ReservationSuccess`; `ManageTables` + `manage-members/*` (troop hub); quartermaster UI under `manage-inventory/*`.
- **`frontend/src/context/CartContext.jsx`** — Cart state + `localStorage` (`scout_gear_cart`, 72h expiry). **`frontend/src/hooks/useInventory.js`** — `fetch`/`post` to `/api` (dev: Vite proxy to backend; prod: `VITE_API_URL`).
- **`backend/server.js`** — Express: CORS, JSON, static `frontend/dist`, API under `/api`, SPA fallback for non-API routes. Dev-only `middleware/dev-security.js`.
- **`backend/services/supabase-api.js`** — **Single** Supabase client; all inventory, checkout/checkin, transactions, metadata/categories, manage-inventory, and reservations logic.
- **`backend/routes/`** — `inventory.js`, `checkout.js`, `checkin.js`, `metadata.js`, `manage-inventory.js`, `reservations.js`. Bulk test helpers on checkout/checkin `POST .../test-bulk`.
- **`backend/services/email-service.js`** — Reservation confirmation (non-blocking).
- **`frontend/scripts/pregenImages.js`** — Generates **`src/utils/optimizedImageList.js`** (gitignored; run via `npm run pregen` or `postinstall` in `frontend/`).
- **Note:** `OutingSelection.jsx` exists but is **not** registered in `App.jsx` routes (legacy/unused unless wired back).

## Terminology (Scouts BSA)

- The app serves a **Scouts BSA** troop (youth and adults). Prefer **Scouts BSA** / **scouting** in UI and docs over legacy “Boy Scouts” branding unless quoting historical text.

**Why this stack:**
- Fast development with Vite's hot reload
- Excellent mobile performance
- Simple deployment to Render
- Familiar technologies that are easy to maintain
- Supabase provides a managed PostgreSQL database with a simple JS client
- No sync complexity — all reads and writes go directly to Supabase

## Mobile UI Flow Design
The system follows an e-commerce shopping cart pattern familiar to users:

### Checkout Process Flow:
1. **Landing Page** - Two large buttons: "Check Out Gear" and "Check In Gear"
2. **Category Selection** - Scrollable list of ~20 gear categories with search functionality
3. **Item Selection** - Category-specific item selection (individual items like TENT-001, TENT-002, SPOON-001, SPOON-002)
4. **Shopping Cart** - Review selected items, add more, or proceed
5. **Scout Information** - Capture scout name, outing name, date, and notes
6. **Confirmation** - Complete checkout and show success message

### Key Mobile UX Features:
- Shopping cart with persistent item counter
- Search functionality always visible on category page
- Large, touch-friendly buttons and controls (44px+ touch targets)
- Clear navigation breadcrumbs and back buttons
- Real-time availability checking
- Responsive design that works on all mobile screen sizes

## Gear UI design (mirror for new screens)

Use the same visual language as the **gear flow** (`Landing.jsx` → `Categories`, `Items`, `Cart`, `Checkout`, `Checkin`, `Reservations.jsx`) and **manage inventory** so troop-hub and QM tools feel like one app.

### Layout shell
- **Page:** `h-screen-small flex flex-col bg-gray-100` (full-height column; `h-screen-small` = `100svh` in `index.css`).
- **Header:** use the `.header` class (scout blue `#1E398A`, sticky, flex row). Center title: `<h1>` with flex spacer: back control + `h1` + `w-10 h-10` (or `h-10 w-10`) placeholder for balance.
- **Back:** `.back-button` inside `.header` (circular light overlay on blue).
- **Reserve mode accent:** optional `.header-reserve` (orange) when the flow is reservation-specific (see `Categories`).

### Brand colors (Tailwind)
Defined in `frontend/src/index.css` (`@theme`): **`scout-blue`** primary actions and header; **`scout-green`** check-in; **`scout-red`** destructive; **`scout-orange`** reservations / secondary CTAs. Prefer these over ad-hoc hex values.

### Cards and lists
- **List rows / panels:** `.card` — white background, `border` gray, `rounded-xl`, light shadow; hover tightens border toward scout blue (see `index.css`).
- **Titles on cards:** `font-semibold text-gray-900`; secondary lines: `text-sm text-gray-500` or `text-gray-600` with `mt-0.5`.
- **Empty states:** `text-center text-sm text-gray-500` with vertical padding (e.g. `py-10`).

### Forms
- **Text / search:** `.search-input` — pill shape, gray border, scout-blue focus ring (16px+ font to avoid iOS zoom).
- **Primary full-width actions:** `w-full h-12 rounded-md bg-scout-blue text-white text-base font-medium` + `disabled:opacity-50` + `touch-target` where appropriate (matches e.g. Reservations “Create Reservation”, form saves).
- **Segmented / tab controls:** `SegmentedControl` — active tab `bg-scout-blue text-white`; use `type="button"` on inner buttons when inside a `<form>`.

### Confirmations (destructive)
- **Do not use** `window.confirm` for flows that should match the app. Use the **bottom sheet** pattern from `Reservations.jsx` (delete reservation):
  - Overlay: `fixed inset-0 z-50 flex items-end justify-center bg-black/40`
  - Sheet: `w-full max-w-md bg-white rounded-t-2xl px-5 pt-5 pb-8`
  - Title: `text-lg font-bold text-gray-900`; body: `text-sm text-gray-600` / `text-gray-500`
  - Actions row: `flex gap-3`; **Cancel** — `flex-1 h-12 rounded-md border border-gray-300 text-sm font-medium text-gray-700`; **Confirm delete** — `flex-1 h-12 rounded-md bg-scout-red text-white text-sm font-medium`

### Touch and density
- Prefer **44px minimum** touch targets (`.touch-target` in `index.css`); large tap areas on phones first.

### Reference files
- **Hero / hub:** `frontend/src/pages/Landing.jsx`
- **List + search + cards:** `frontend/src/pages/Categories.jsx`, `frontend/src/pages/Reservations.jsx`
- **Destructive confirm sheet:** `frontend/src/pages/Reservations.jsx` (delete block at bottom of file)

## Data Model

### 1. Master Inventory (`items` table in Supabase)
Updated when check out/in occurs. Each row represents a unique item.
Some items like TENT-001 get physical tags. Other items are fungible like SPOON-001 and SPOON-002 - we track individual spoons but they're interchangeable.

**Columns:**
- `Item Class` - e.g. TENT, BRCAN (bear can)
- `Item Desc` - long description of class, e.g. Bear Can for BRCAN
- `Item Num` - 3 digit suffix sequence number to uniquely identify item in a class, e.g. 001, 002
- `Item ID` - Unique identifier (TENT-001, SPOON-001)
- `Description` - Human-readable item description, e.g. Zephyr 3 or Half Dome 2+
- `Is Tagged` - boolean, true when item has a printed tag that can be attached to item
- `Condition` - Usable, Not usable, Unknown
- `Status` - In shed, Checked out, Missing, Out for repair
- `Purchase Date` - When item was acquired
- `Cost` - Purchase price if known
- `Checked Out To` - Current holder (scout name)
- `Checked Out By` - For accountability, who processed the checkout
- `Check Out Date` - When item was checked out
- `Outing Name` - Current outing assignment
- `Notes` - Additional information

### 2. Transaction Log (`transactions` table in Supabase)
Append-only audit trail of all checkout/checkin activities.

**Columns:**
- `Transaction ID` - Unique transaction identifier (auto-generated)
- `Timestamp` - When transaction occurred
- `Action` - "Check in" or "Check out"
- `Item ID` - Which item was affected, e.g. TENT-001
- `Outing Name` - Associated outing
- `Condition` - Item condition (for checkin transactions). Values: Usable, Not usable, Unknown
- `Processed By` - System user who processed (for accountability)
- `Notes` - Additional transaction details

## Technical Implementation Plan

### Repository layout (actual)

- **`frontend/src/`** — `components/` (e.g. `Toast`, `ConnectionError`), `pages/`, `hooks/`, `context/`, `utils/`, `App.jsx`.
- **`backend/`** — `routes/`, `services/supabase-api.js`, `middleware/`, `server.js`, `utils/`.

### Core API surface (prefix `/api`)

- **Inventory** — `GET /inventory`, `/inventory/categories`, `/inventory/items/:category`, `/inventory/outings`, `/inventory/checked-out/:outing`, `/inventory/outing-details/:outing`.
- **Checkout / check-in** — `POST /checkout`, `POST /checkin` (body: item IDs, names, outing, etc.).
- **Metadata** — categories CRUD for `metadata` table (used by manage UI).
- **Manage inventory** — items and category stats under `/manage-inventory/*`.
- **Reservations** — `GET/POST/DELETE /reservations`, `GET /reservations/:outingName`.
- **Ops** — `GET /health`, `GET /ping`.

### Supabase Integration:
- Use `@supabase/supabase-js` npm package for all database access
- **Single service file** `backend/services/supabase-api.js` — no legacy sync layer
- **No sync layer** — all reads and writes go directly to Supabase; no wipe-and-repopulate pattern
- **Service key authentication** via `SUPABASE_URL` and `SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY` environment variables
- **Error handling** with try/catch on all async operations
- **Data validation** on both client and server sides

### Supabase Client Setup:
```javascript
const { createClient } = require('@supabase/supabase-js');
const supabase = createClient(process.env.SUPABASE_URL, process.env.SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY);
```

### Supabase schema (core tables):
- `items` — master inventory (one row per item); `in_app` gates visibility in public checkout; soft delete via `status = 'Removed from inventory'`.
- `transactions` — append-only audit trail
- `metadata` — gear categories (`class` + `class_desc`; class code immutable)
- `reservations` — active reservation rows; reserved items use `items.status = 'Reserved'` and `outing_name`

## Development Approach
- Start with basic checkout flow: Categories → Items → Cart → Checkout
- Mobile-first responsive design using Tailwind CSS
- Component-based architecture for reusability
- Simple state management (React context or useState)
